name.text: 12.1.2.1 Tangents and normals to a curve

questiontext.text:
Tangents and normals to a curve

As we know, the relationship between an independent variable \(x\) and a dependent variable \(y\) is denoted by

 \(\qquad y=f(x)\)

As we also know, the geometrical interpretation of this relation takes the form of a curve in an \(xy\) plane as illustrated in the Figure below.

We know how to calculate a value of \(y\) given a value of \(x\). We can either do this graphically (which is inaccurate) or else use the function itself. So, at an \(x\) value of \(x_0\), the corresponding \(y\) value is \(y_0\) where 

\(\qquad y_0=f(x_0)\)

Let us examine the curve in the neighbourhood of the point \((x_0,y_0)\). There are two important constructions of interest

  • the tangent line at \((x_0,y_0)\)
  • the normal line at \((x_0,y_0)\)

These are shown in the following Figure:

We note the geometrically obvious fact: the tangent and normal lines at any given point on a curve are perpendicular to each other.

  1. The curve \(y=x^2\) is drawn below. On the Figure below, draw the tangent line and the normal line at the point \((x_0=1,y_0=1)\):

  2. From the graph, estimate the values of \(\theta\) and \(\psi\) in degrees. (You will need a protractor.)

Solution


  2. \(\theta ≈ 63.4^{\circ}, \qquad \psi ≈ 153.4^{\circ}\)

 

Returning to the curve \(y=f(x)\) we know, from the geometrical interpretation of the derivative, that 

\(\qquad \dfrac{df}{dx}\bigg|_{x_0}=\tan\theta\)

(the notation \(\dfrac{df}{dx}\bigg|_{x_0}\) means evaluate \(\dfrac{df}{dx}\) at the value \(x=x_0\))
